{"info": {"author": "Michael Martinez", "author_email": "imichael@pm.me", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["Development Status :: 3 - Alpha", "Intended Audience :: Developers", "License :: OSI Approved :: MIT License", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.5", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.6", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.7", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.8", "Topic :: Software Development :: Build Tools"], "description": "# PipFlow\n\n\n## Background\n\nPipflow is built for developers who deploy their Python software using Docker and Cloud Native technologies. When \nbuilding docker images our constraints are:\n\n- The more slim the image, the better.\n- The less image layers, the better.\n- Don't reinvent the wheel by installing a new package manager in your Dockerfile. These tools tend to use \n  lock files, which are fine in general, but in Docker they are redundant because we already have a way to \n  pin dependencies: Docker image layers.\n\n\nThis leave us with one option: Continue to use plain old `pip`, but create some new workflows that improve the \ndeveloper experience.\n\nFor example, Pipflow replaces this workflow:\n\n\n    $ pip3 install <new-package>\n    $ pip3 freeze | grep <new-package> >> requirements.txt\n    $ docker build ... # (A redudant install)\n\n\nwith this:\n\n    $ pipflow add <package>\n\n\n## Setup\nInstall `pipflow` on your *HOST OS only* (macOS, Windows, Linux etc). Do not add Pipflow to your `requirements.txt`.\n\n    pip3 install pipflow\n\n## Usage\n\nAdd a new package\n\n    pipflow add <package-name>\n\nRemove a package\n\n    pipflow remove <package-name>\n\nUpgrade a package version\n\n    pipflow upgrade <package-name>\n\nUpgrade all packages\n\n    pipflow upgrade-all\n\n\nVew all packages eligible for upgrade\n\n    pipflow view-all\n\n## License\nMIT Copyright (c) 2020 Michael.\n\n\n", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://github.com/iMerica/pipflow", "keywords": "Package Managers", "license": "", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "Pipflow", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/Pipflow/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/Pipflow/", "project_urls": {"Homepage": "https://github.com/iMerica/pipflow"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/Pipflow/0.0.6/", "requires_dist": ["cleo", "requests"], "requires_python": ">=3.5", "summary": "Python Distribution Utilities", "version": "0.0.6", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <h1>PipFlow</h1>\n<h2>Background</h2>\n<p>Pipflow is built for developers who deploy their Python software using Docker and Cloud Native technologies. When\nbuilding docker images our constraints are:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>The more slim the image, the better.</li>\n<li>The less image layers, the better.</li>\n<li>Don't reinvent the wheel by installing a new package manager in your Dockerfile. These tools tend to use\nlock files, which are fine in general, but in Docker they are redundant because we already have a way to\npin dependencies: Docker image layers.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This leave us with one option: Continue to use plain old <code>pip</code>, but create some new workflows that improve the\ndeveloper experience.</p>\n<p>For example, Pipflow replaces this workflow:</p>\n<pre><code>$ pip3 install &lt;new-package&gt;\n$ pip3 freeze | grep &lt;new-package&gt; &gt;&gt; requirements.txt\n$ docker build ... # (A redudant install)\n</code></pre>\n<p>with this:</p>\n<pre><code>$ pipflow add &lt;package&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<h2>Setup</h2>\n<p>Install <code>pipflow</code> on your <em>HOST OS only</em> (macOS, Windows, Linux etc). Do not add Pipflow to your <code>requirements.txt</code>.</p>\n<pre><code>pip3 install pipflow\n</code></pre>\n<h2>Usage</h2>\n<p>Add a new package</p>\n<pre><code>pipflow add &lt;package-name&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Remove a package</p>\n<pre><code>pipflow remove &lt;package-name&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Upgrade a package version</p>\n<pre><code>pipflow upgrade &lt;package-name&gt;\n</code></pre>\n<p>Upgrade all packages</p>\n<pre><code>pipflow upgrade-all\n</code></pre>\n<p>Vew all packages eligible for upgrade</p>\n<pre><code>pipflow view-all\n</code></pre>\n<h2>License</h2>\n<p>MIT Copyright (c) 2020 Michael.</p>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 6533991, "releases": {"0.0.1": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "4eaa51dd1316a79589803e0725105b1c", "sha256": "a4a6a7f58431edb42d718fb14c8a84380ca74928ca661ace95ee17350cdf64f1"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "Pipflow-0.0.1-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "4eaa51dd1316a79589803e0725105b1c", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py3", "requires_python": ">=3.5", "size": 4768, "upload_time": "2020-01-08T18:08:54", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2020-01-08T18:08:54.487243Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/4d/6d/4fae8db6b4993cf68f30a7baaa158551dfa88c5ef595fc2ee6de9990e12b/Pipflow-0.0.1-py3-none-any.whl", "yanked": false}], "0.0.2": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "7d5c2b9f9bf5a00990d2e9d5f7be7105", "sha256": "0d4b01d4140093b7ebd5120e77b33e86669b7f34b9e7fed3024817ca30e6b124"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "Pipflow-0.0.2-py3-none-any.whl", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "7d5c2b9f9bf5a00990d2e9d5f7be7105", "packagetype": "bdist_wheel", "python_version": "py3", "requires_python": ">=3.5", "size": 4744, "upload_time": "2020-01-08T18:17:18", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2020-01-08T18:17:18.534743Z", "url": "https://files.pythonhosted.org/packages/31/f9/a2973ff31e25d510c8d95a845f179e5df00538afc437b1f86e5b098cfbc2/Pipflow-0.0.2-py3-none-any.whl", "yanked": false}], "0.0.3": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "d84748089eab0f8a8ea448455b074813", "sha256": "a98380e3d1b1ad45e7328356154369b1507f50216498e18872a975373e1a36e1"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "Pipflow-0.0.3-py3-none